nicity serve as forms of currency in American literature, affording people of color material and symbolic wages as they traverse class divisions. Identifying four recurring character types-status seekers, conflicted artists, mediators, and gatekeepers-that appear across genres, Román traces how each models a distinct strategy for negotiating race and class. Her comparative analysis sheds light on the overlaps and misalignments, the shared narrative strategies, and the historical trajectories of Mexican American and African American texts, bringing both groups' works into sharper relief. Her study advances both a new approach to ethnic literary studies and a more nuanced understanding of the class-based complexities of racial identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aSocial classes in literature. 0aSocial mobility in literature. 4aAfrican American literature. 4aAfrican American. 4aChicana/o. 4aLatina/o literature. 4aLatina/o. 4aminority middle class. 4asocial class. 4aupward mobility. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360388240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603882.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles